navigate the twentieth century with its imperial territorial expanse largely intact. In Birth of the Geopolitical Age, Shellen Xiao Wu demonstrates how global examples of frontier settlements refracted through China's unique history and informed the making of the modern Chinese state. Wu weaves a narrative that moves through time and space, the lives of individuals, and empires' rise and fall and rebirth, to show how the subsequent reshaping of Chinese geopolitical ambitions in the twentieth century, and the global transformation of frontiers into colonial laboratories, continues to reorder global power dynamics in East Asia and the wider world to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBorderlandszChinaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBorderlandszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aColonizationxHistoryy19th century. 0aColonizationxHistoryy20th century. 0aGeopoliticszChinaxHistoryy19th century. 0aGeopoliticszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aagricultural science.  aagronomy.  aborderlands.  aempire.  aexperimental zones.  afrontiers.  ageography.  ageopolitics.  anetwork science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363685940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503636859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503636859/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles